## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+
2. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** — your catch block is dead code
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**

### Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was always dangerous — it could corrupt shared state, interrupt `finally` blocks, and leave locks held. .NET Core replaced it with **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cooperative shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (cooperative — not forced)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for the worker to finish, with a timeout
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Abort(). You must fix
            // GetNextItemAsync/ProcessItemAsync to honor the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Socket`, `Console.ReadLine`, etc., cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` into I/O calls. |
| **No forced kill exists** | .NET 8 has no `Abort()` replacement. If code doesn't respect the token, it keeps running. Design for cooperation. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` instead. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | It can't wake a blocked call. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async` APIs, `WaitHandle`, and `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)`. |
| **Sync-over-async deadlocks** | If you keep `ProcessLoop` synchronous but call `.Result` on async APIs inside it, you risk deadlocks. Go fully async. |

### If You Can't Make Dependencies Async

For legacy code where `GetNextItem()` is synchronous and blocking:

```csharp
// Wrap blocking call so cancellation still works
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Run blocking work off the calling context
    return await Task.Run(() =>
    {
        // Poll-based cancellation for truly uninterruptible calls
        while (!_blockingCollection.TryTake(out var item, 500))
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        }
        return item;
    }, token);
}
```

### Also Consider: `BackgroundService`

If this runs in ASP.NET Core or a Generic Host app, inherit from `BackgroundService` instead of managing threads yourself:

```csharp
public class MyProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration in Program.cs:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<MyProcessor>();
```

The host handles `Start`/`Stop` lifecycle, graceful shutdown, and cancellation token wiring for you.
